Introduction

This dataset, originally described by Cortez et al. 2009 contains 4,898 white wines with 11 variables quantifying the chemical properties of each wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). This link describes of the variables and how the data was collected. I am interested in investigating which chemical properties influence the quality of white wines.

Univariate Plots Section

As expected there are 4898 white wines, with 12 columns (11 physicochemical properties and 1 quality rating).

For all variables the median and the mean are close together suggesting that these parameters will not be highly skewed. The median (5.2) and mean (6.3) of the residual sugar variable are the farthest apart suggesting that there may be some outliers on the high end (for example the max of 65.8). It is surprising to observe a fold difference of over 100 between the minimum and maximum values for residual sugar and free sulfur dioxide. The alcohol content ranges from 8.0 - 14.2%. The scale for quality was 1-10; however, the ratings given only range from 3-9, with a median rating of 6.

The histogram of fixed acidity appears to be normally distributed.

The histogram of volatile acidity is slightly skewed to the right. I will log10 transform this data to see if it makes the histogram normally distributed.

Now volatile acidity is normally distributed.

The bulk of the data of citric acid is normally distributed with an outlier of 1.66 pulling the skew to the right.

When the top 1% of citric acid data is removed the data appear normally distributed.

The histogram of residual sugar is skewed to the right. This graph has the bin with the highest count near the left with a wide right tail and an outlier at 65.8.

Transforming the data using a log10 scale does not make the data normally distributed, but bimodal.

The histogram of chlorides is skewed to the right with a long thin tail.

Transforming the chlorides data using log10 makes the data appear more normally distributed.

The histogram of free sulfur dioxide levels appears to be slightly skewed to the right with a very small and thin tail and an outlier at 289.

When excluding the top 1% of free sulfur dioxide levels, the data appear more symmetric, however, the data looks more like a pyramid instead of normally distributed.

The histogram of total sulfur dioxide generally looks normally distributed with an extremely thin right tail.

The histogram of density appears to be normally distributed with a very thin right tail and an outlier at 1.039. The majority of densities are close to, but below, 1 which makes sense given the density of water being 1 and alcohol being less than 1. I’m unsure what would cause a wine to have a density above 1.

The histogram of pH appears to be normally distributed.

The histogram of sulphates appears to be skewed to the right.

Graphing sulphates on a log10 scale transforms the data to be normally distributed.

The histogram of alcohol levels is skewed to the right with a wide tail.

Graphing the alcohol data on a log10 scale makes the data more symmetric but does not appear normally distributed as the peak of the data is wide.

The quality rating with the highest count is 6 and the data are largely symmetric as the ratings for 5 and 7 are slightly lower, 4 and 8 are even lower, 3 and 9 are very low, and 0, 1, 2 and 10 are absent.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset contains data on 4898 white wines with 12 columns (11 physicochemical properties and 1 quality rating). All of the 11 physicochemical properties are of the numeric type (contains decimals) while the quality values are integers.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I would like to investigate which physicochemical properties of the wine influence the quality rating; therefore, the quality rating is the most important feature in this data.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I will investigate all 11 properties of the wines to determine whether they influence quality. Given my limited knowledge of wine and these specific physicochemical properties, I cannot predict which features will affect quality. In addition, the univariate analyses alone does not shed light on which variables will be the most important therefore I will investigate them all in the bivariate section.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I have not created any new variables yet. This may change after further investigation into the bi- and multi-variate analyses.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The data was already tidy therefore no adjustments were made.

Bivariate Plots Section

Although I am most interested in determining if any of these physicochemical properties influence quality, we will investigate all relationships first to better understand the data. I will report on correlations that are equal to or greater than |0.3| when rounded to 1 decimal point with correlations between |0.3| and |0.7| to be considered moderate and above |0.7| to be strong.

fixed acidity vs citric acid 0.3 fixed acidity vs pH -0.4

free sulfur dioxide vs residual sugar 0.3 free sulfur dioxide vs total sulfur dioxide 0.6

density vs fixed acidity 0.3 density vs residual sugar 0.8 density vs chlorides 0.3 density vs free sulfur dioxide 0.3 density vs total sulfur dioxide 0.5

alcohol vs density -0.8 alcohol vs residual sugar -0.5 alcohol vs chlorides -0.4 alcohol vs free sulfur dioxide -0.3 alcohol vs total sulfur dioxide -0.5

quality vs alcohol 0.4 quality vs density -0.3

It is logical that fixed acidity would be positively correlated to citric acid and negatively correlated to pH given each that each parameter is related to acidity.

As expected free and total sulfur dioxide levels are strongly positively correlated to one another since total levels are equal to free levels + bound levels of sulfur dioxide.

Interestingly density and alcohol were correlated to many other parameters. It makes sense that density would increase with increasing solutes (residual sugar, chlorides, etc.) but I’m assuming that because density decreases with increasing alcohol levels (given the density of alcohol vs water) this explains why alcohol is therefore negatively correlated to these solutes as well.

The only parameters that are related to quality are alcohol (which are moderately positive correlated), and density (which are moderately negative correlated).

Graphing the data with quality on a continuous scale I am able to add a linear fit line through the data showing that as alcohol levels increase, quality levels increase. However, despite the transparency of the points, it is difficult to visualize the extent of the overlap between each quality group. Therefore, I have graphed same data using jittering to see more points, as well as see the 5 point summary in a boxplot as shown below.

In the graph on the left we can see that the majority of the data falls in quality rating 5, 6 and 7, less data falls in a rating of 4 and 8, even less so in the rating of 3, and only five points in a rating of 9. There is a great deal of overlap between each sequential rating.

Interestingly, in the graph on the right, it looks like the alcohol rating tends to decrease from a quality rating of 3 to 5, and increases from 5 to 9. The group with the least variability is the quality rating of 9 where 80% of the points are clustered together at a high alcohol rating. However, there is
a very low N (only 5 observations in this category), and variability may increase with more observations.

It looks like the 2 outliers with a density above 1.01 are making it more difficult to view the bulk of the data. I will exclude these points and graph the plot again.

Applying the linear model line on the data we can see that with increasing density there is a decrease in quality.

Similar to the alcohol vs quality plots, the density vs quality plots also exhibit significant overlap between the quality groups. Because density and alcohol are related (increased alcohol leads to decreased density), again we observe the least variability in the group with a quality rating of 9 where 80% of the points are clustered together at a low density level.

So far it does not appear that either alcohol or density (or anything else) are strong indicators of quality. Therefore, to investigate the strongest correlation observed I will graph density vs alcohol.

This indeed is a stronger relationship. Again this is not surprising given that alcohol is less dense than water. However, I anticipate that predicting density (rather than qulity) will end up being more fruitful using predictive models, albeit potentially less interesting.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Using the scatterplot matrix I was able to quickly observe the correlations between all variables. It was not surprising that fixed acidity was positively correlated to citric acid and negatively correlated to pH given each that each parameter is related to acidity. In addition, free and total sulfur dioxide levels are strongly positively correlated to one another since total levels are equal to free levels + bound levels of sulfur dioxide.

Unfortunately, alcohol and density were only weakly to moderately correlated to quality (0.4 and -0.3 respectively), and therefore I do not anticipate that the predictive model I will generate in the next section will be very accurate.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

What was more interesting to me was the relationship between density and alcohol, as well as the relationship between each of these parameters to fixed acidity, residual sugar, chlorides, and total sulfur dioxide levels. I anticipate that the predictive model generated for predicting density will be more accurate than the one predicting quality.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationships found were density vs residual sugar (0.8) and density vs alcohol (-0.8).

Multivariate Plots Section

I am first going to attempt to make a predictive model for quality. Quality was most strongly correlated to alcohol and I would like to see if any other variables help explain the variability seen in the quality vs alcohol graph.

##    Low Medium   High 
##   1715   1383   1800

For all instances of me dividing up variables into 3 roughly equal-sized groups, I chose the values manually as I was curious to play around with the numbers; however, I believe there is also a easy to cut them into 3 equal groups automatically.

Density appears to be more correlated to alcohol levels alone, opposed to explaining the variability in this graph. Next, I will look at the residual sugar level, which was highly correlated to density (which was moderately correlated to quality).

##    Low Medium   High 
##   1500   1776   1622

The different colored points (varied residual sugar levels) appear to be equally distributed throughout the plot and therefore likely do not explain the variability observed.

For curiosity’s sake I will generate a predictive model incorporating alcohol first, then adding on other variables to see their effect on the R-squared value of the model. However, I anticipate that the model will be very poor.

m1 using alcohol alone as a predicter elicited a R-squared value of only 0.190. Adding on density, residual sugar, and chlorides alone increased the R-squared value minutely. m6 using all of these parameters had the highest R-squared value of 0.212 which is still a very poor model. Again, out of curiosity I wanted to determine how large the 95% confidence intervals would be when predicting a wine with the median value for all variables, as well as a wine with a quality rating of 9.

##        fit     lwr      upr

Moving away from quality, would like to try and predict the density of wine based on the alcohol levels, as well as additional parameters starting with residual sugar.

Residual sugar appears to explain some of the variability in the density vs alcohol graph since the points above the linear line of best fit have the highest sugar levels, and the observations below the line contain the lowest sugar levels.

##    Low Medium   High

##    Low Medium   High 
##   1575   1533   1790

Fixed acidity levels may explain some of the variability in the plot of density vs alcohol since the highest points at any given alcohol level tend to be darker (higher fixed acidity) while the lowest points tend to be the lightest (lowest fixed acidity).

Alcohol as a single variable produced an R-squared value of 0.609 when explaining the density levels. Adding residual sugar, fixed acidity, and total sulfur dioxide levels into the equation increased the R-squared value to 0.907, 0.930, and 0.933 respectively. There may be parameters that were not measured the explain the remainder of the variability in density levels. This R-squared value is much higher than the predictive model for quality, and I anticipate that it will be able to accurately predict density levels which is tested below.

Surprisingly despite the R-squared value of 0.933, the true density of the wine (0.997) didn’t land within the 95% confidence interval. Perhaps I put too much hope in this model because the R-squared value was so much higher than that of the model predicting quality, but the R-squared value may need to be closer to 1 to better predict density.

For the multivariate analysis of quality, I did not find anything useful beyond alcohol and density that could explain quality levels, and this resulted in a very poor predictive model. Interestingly, I found that a combination of alcohol and residual sugar levels can largely explain density levels (and fixed acidity and total sulfur dioxide levels help the prediction slightly more.)

The predictive model for density was much better than quality with an R-squared value of 0.933, however this was still unable to predict the density of a wine within the 95% confidence interval. There must be other parameters that explain density that were not included in this dataset.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Firstly, I wanted variety in the appearance of my final plots so I chose this one even though it may be unusual to graph a scatterplot when the quality ratings are descrete. I thought this graph was important because it represents the strongest correlation between any variable and quality which ended up being alcohol.

Plot Two

Description Two

I chose this graph as it was a different way to represent the type of data shown in Plot 1. The boxplot allows you to glean information such as the 5 number summary, outliers, overlap between groups, and trends across quality ratings.

Plot Three

Description Three

The strongest relationships found were between density vs alcohol (-0.8) and density vs residual sugar (0.8) and this multivariate plot was able to display all three variables at once. It appears that residual sugar levels explain some of the variability in the density vs alcohol plot, and alcohol and residual sugar alone were able to predict density levels with an R-squared value of 0.907.

Reflection

I found that plotting all the histograms in the univariate plots was tedious, boring, and not very informative since it is not intuitive what all the variables mean, or the significance of the values.

I was disappointed that I wasn’t able to find anything that strongly correlated with the quality of wine, and that the predictive model was so poor. For something like the diamonds dataset, it is more intuitive that you’d be able to predict the price of a diamond - generally, the bigger, the better. However, with wine, quality can be quite subjective, especially for an expert vs a non-expert. Some people love sweet and some people hate it. Some people may be turned off if the alcohol taste is too strong. Some experts might be swayed by hints of flavors and depth of taste while I just hope the wine doesn’t taste like cleaner.

After doing a more in-depth investigation into what dictates density I was a little more excited and willing to complete this project. Although it is obvious that alcohol levels and solutes will affect density, it was fun to play with the predictions using the linear models.

For future analysis, I think it would be interesting if use more complicated modelling techniques to create more accurate predictive models such as those used in this R Pubs post.
